You can do it too  too… Here are some tips for being a super dad:
1. Be present: Being a super dad means being there for your kids and actively engaging with them. Make time for one-on-one activities with each of your children, whether it’s playing catch, going for a walk, or reading together.
2. Lead by example: Kids look up to their dads, so it’s important to model positive behaviors and values. Show your kids how to be respectful, kind, responsible, and hardworking by setting a good example.
3. Listen actively: Listening to your kids can help strengthen your relationship and build trust. Practice active listening by giving your full attention, asking open-ended questions, and reflecting back what you’ve heard.
4. Show affection: Kids need physical affection and emotional support from their dads. Hugs, kisses, and positive affirmations can go a long way in making your kids feel loved and valued.
5. Encourage independence: Part of being a super dad is helping your kids become independent and self-reliant. Encourage your kids to take on age-appropriate responsibilities and support them as they learn new skills.
6. Be flexible: Parenting can be unpredictable, so it’s important to be flexible and adaptable. Be willing to adjust your plans and routines as needed to accommodate your kids’ needs and interests.
7. Take care of yourself: Being a super dad also means taking care of your own physical and mental health. Make time for exercise, hobbies, and self-care activities that help you feel refreshed and energized.
By following these tips, you can become a super dad who nurtures strong, healthy relationships with your kids and helps them grow into happy, confident adults.

By helping kids develop a positive mindset and a strong sense of self-worth, affirmations can set them up for success in all areas of their lives.

Here are some reasons why affirmations are important for kids:
1. Boost self-confidence: Affirmations can help children feel more confident and self-assured. When kids repeat positive statements about themselves, it can help them believe in their own abilities and potential.
2. Encourage a growth mindset: Affirmations can also help kids develop a growth mindset, which is the belief that their abilities can be developed through hard work and dedication. When kids repeat affirmations like “I can learn anything I set my mind to,” it can help them develop a positive attitude towards learning and growth.
3. Promote positive self-talk: Affirmations can help kids develop a habit of positive self-talk, which can improve their overall mental health and well-being. When kids learn to speak positively about themselves, it can help reduce feelings of self-doubt and anxiety.
4. Counter negative messages: Kids are often bombarded with negative messages from society, media, and even their own inner critic. Affirmations can help counter these negative messages and provide kids with a positive, uplifting message to focus on instead.
5. Foster a sense of gratitude: Affirmations can also help kids develop a sense of gratitude for the positive things in their lives. When kids repeat affirmations like “I am thankful for all the good things in my life,” it can help them appreciate what they have and feel more content.

Experts reveals why KIDS MISBEHAVE around their MOMS 
 {I learned something today}

A study conducted by DR. KP. Leibowitz of the department of psychology at the university of washington in the united states found that children behave 800 times worse in the presence of their mother compared to when they are with other people or with their father 

The research on 500 families measured the children by considering the following variables :
complain,crying,screaming,hitting attempts,asking for many things,throwing toys,or even forgetting how to walk or talk 

The conclusion was that when perceiving the scent of their mothers the children felt the need to call their attention constantly.

📌This is a behavior typical of young Children, Who are learning to Control and express Their Emotions they See you as a safe place and try to be themselves, so it is important that you teach them the limits. You must do this clearly, and it is a task that requires patience and love.

When I first held my daughter and she opened her eyes and looked me in the face, that’s all it took… I WAS SOLD ON BEING A DAD.
👇🏼👇🏼
I was scared as hell + I had no idea what to do if.

Everything had to be different from
what I experienced —meaning  BE BETTER,  Showing up. Saying and showing love. Being apart of their activities, lives, having fun & learning who they are.I promised myself to be the BEST father my family has EVER had. 

 I was somehow failing & doing something wrong working  70+ hrs a wk & my kids were sleep, or in bed when I got home only for me to repeat it the next day.. .

I was playing the exact tune I grew up to. All work no time for my babies.

 I was missing in my babies lives …& honestly they were growing up and I was missing it ALL? 

I stopped doubting myself and made sure Cliff Huxtable & all the other TV DADS had nothing on me at all.
 
I couldn’t fail because my family was depending on me. Greatness waits on no one so I went out and found it.

I’d like to say that one day the lightbulb just switched on and I realized the lives + futures and all the feelings were there and being afraid wasn’t going to work.

but it definitely took time and even now I’m still learning to be a great dad…

Learning to live +  laugh & love. To not always rush to be so critical at my little people’s mistakes but pause for the important things to learn + relish in the timeless moments. 

To be proud + grateful for what I’ve accomplished as a father, husband — even if it was mostly unseen things that no one else will notice, applaud, or pay me for...

And to give myself permission to not always be so fast to anger- but instead, accept that the fathering 3 different personalities  matters + therefore I am allowed to take up my time learn and get better.

As Phillip Banks put it, “A real man takes responsibility for his actions. A real man knows when to let go of his pride and make the most out of his second chance.”

So when my kids are all playing together & it’s loud and they are all making a mess (after I just cleaned up) I take it all in and just smile:

All these moments matter 🤍
I blame the shorts 😂

Pretty hard 😂
